      {
         "id": "SECTION_introduction",
         "text": [
            {
               "text": "### Introduction\n\nThe *First Steps* section aimed to introduce fundamental concepts from different sciences.\n\nHowever, as Dr. Francisco González A. Redondo points out in various works and lectures, everything we have seen so far is only part of what we can call \"pre-mathematics\" (<htcite0>; <htcite1>; <htcite2>; <htcite3>).\n\nWith everything learned up to this point, reflect:",
               "source": [
                  {
                     "type": 1,
                     "uuid": "d6a6b284-a060-4a85-bc6c-9d2fe442254c",
                     "text": "Francisco González A. Redondo",
                     "page": "",
                     "date_time": {
                        "type": "gregory",
                        "year": "2024",
                        "month": "",
                        "day": ""
                     }
                  },
                  {
                     "type": 1,
                     "uuid": "cd61bc64-1358-4bfd-b343-3629facaa3b4",
                     "text": "Francisco González A. Redondo",
                     "page": "",
                     "date_time": {
                        "type": "gregory",
                        "year": "2024",
                        "month": "",
                        "day": ""
                     }
                  },
                  {
                     "type": 1,
                     "uuid": "abc894b4-61b2-4f0f-a145-9d591cda41d2",
                     "text": "Francisco González A. Redondo",
                     "page": "",
                     "date_time": {
                        "type": "gregory",
                        "year": "2014",
                        "month": "",
                        "day": ""
                     }
                  },
                  {
                     "type": 1,
                     "uuid": "81e9393b-d5b6-4b04-91bd-417e943d3e97",
                     "text": "History Tracers Team",
                     "page": "The Knowledge",
                     "date_time": {
                        "type": "gregory",
                        "year": "",
                        "month": "",
                        "day": ""
                     }
                  }
               ],
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "markdown",
               "PostMention": ""
            },
            {
               "text": "<center><div class=\"first_steps_reflection_parent\"><div class=\"first_steps_reflection question_mark\"><i class=\"fa-solid fa-brain\"></i></div><div class=\"first_steps_reflection\"><b>Reflection 1: It is the foundation for...</b><br /><br />Can you imagine situations where we can use the four operations—addition, multiplication, division, and subtraction—together?</div></div></center>",
               "source": null,
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "html",
               "PostMention": ""
            }
         ]
      },
      {
         "id": "SECTION_couting",
         "text": [
            {
               "text": "### Counting\n\nWhen beginning the study of humanity's discoveries related to the universe, we saw that, using our bodies, we can begin counting with our hands (<htcite0>). As we continued the study, we observed that investigations by Dr. Francisco González A. Redondo *et al.* demonstrated that counting is a practice performed by humanity for at least 37,000 years (<htcite1>).",
               "source": [
                  {
                     "type": 1,
                     "uuid": "3874d1e8-0f76-4432-9ee2-d8c8c9dccf53",
                     "text": "History Tracers Team",
                     "page": "Couting",
                     "date_time": {
                        "type": "gregory",
                        "year": "",
                        "month": "",
                        "day": ""
                     }
                  },
                  {
                     "type": 1,
                     "uuid": "a4f22e25-5839-407f-a1aa-634521d52b42",
                     "text": "González Redondo, Francisco A., et al.",
                     "page": "pp. 180 - 181",
                     "date_time": {
                        "type": "gregory",
                        "year": "2010",
                        "month": "",
                        "day": ""
                     }
                  }
               ],
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "markdown",
               "PostMention": ""
            },
            {
               "text": "<p class=\"desc\"><img id=\"img9\" onclick=\"htImageZoom('img9', '0%')\" src=\"images/ResearchGate/Figura-9-Hueso-de-Lebombo.png\" class=\"imgcenter\"/><b>Figure 3</b>: Representation of baboon bone adorned with markings. This image, credited to Enrique Silván Pobes, is featured in the scholarly work of Francisco A. Gonzáles Redondo et al.<br />The original is available in ResearchNet (<a href=\"#\" onclick=\"htCleanSources(); htFillReferenceSource('adaed4fb-9c50-4ef9-ab79-c65f3c0629b8'); return false;\">González Redondo, Francisco A., et al., <htdate0></a>), and its inclusion here is made possible by the authorization of Doctor Francisco A. Gonzales Redondo.</p><p>Over the centuries, various numeration systems have been utilized, some of which endure to this day. In the following sections, we present an overview of contemporary systems alongside those that have recently fallen out of use.</p>",
               "source": null,
               "date_time": [
                  {
                     "type": "gregory",
                     "year": "2010",
                     "month": "-1",
                     "day": "-1"
                  }
               ],
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "html",
               "PostMention": ""
            },
            {
               "text": "The chapter on counting (* The journey into numbers*) continued by demonstrating that numbers can always be added to other numbers, with no rule preventing this process.\n\nGiven this scenario, mathematicians developed, over the last centuries, the concept of limits, which was also introduced in the first chapter. Using this concept, we learned that when it is not possible to express a quantity through a specific value, we can say we are tending to that value. We also learned that, as numbers grow without end, we can say they tend to infinity (∞) (<htcite0>).",
               "source": [
                  {
                     "type": 1,
                     "uuid": "18a901e4-3da3-45d8-a239-fb551e78698e",
                     "text": "History Tracers Team",
                     "page": "Límites en la Naturaleza",
                     "date_time": {
                        "type": "gregory",
                        "year": "2024",
                        "month": "",
                        "day": ""
                     }
                  }
               ],
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "markdown",
               "PostMention": ""
            }
         ]
      },
      {
         "id": "SECTION_comparing",
         "text": [
            {
               "text": "### Comparing\n\nAfter learning how counting was discovered over time, we moved to a second important stage in the evolution of human knowledge: the act of comparing.\n\nIn this stage of our studies, we observed that the same word can be used to define different types of objects that resemble each other but are not exactly the same. As an example, we studied pyramids and saw how to define them (<htcite0>; <htcite1>):",
               "source": [
                  {
                     "type": 1,
                     "uuid": "1aae32d7-8b8a-49d9-b136-f859e24a53e6",
                     "text": "Weisstein, Eric W.",
                     "page": "Pyramid",
                     "date_time": {
                        "type": "gregory",
                        "year": "",
                        "month": "",
                        "day": ""
                     }
                  },
                  {
                     "type": 1,
                     "uuid": "bb226b7f-2358-437f-b6e1-668943c682d7",
                     "text": "History Tracers Team",
                     "page": "On Equality",
                     "date_time": {
                        "type": "gregory",
                        "year": "2024",
                        "month": "",
                        "day": ""
                     }
                  }
               ],
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "markdown",
               "PostMention": ""
            },
            {
               "text": "<p><table class=\"book_navigation\"><tr><td>Pyramid with a Square Base</td><td>Pyramid with a Pentagonal Base</td></tr><tr><td><img id=\"img2\" onclick=\"htImageZoom('img2', '0%')\" src=\"images/HistoryTracers/pyramid.jpg\" class=\"imgcenter\"/></td><td><img id=\"img3\" onclick=\"htImageZoom('img3', '0%')\" src=\"images/HistoryTracers/pentagonal_pyramid.jpg\" class=\"imgcenter\"/></td></tr><tr><td colspan=\"2\" class=\"desc\"><b>Figure 2</b>: Examples of pyramids illustrating the mathematical definition.</td></tr></table></p><p><ul class=\"citation\"> <li>\"<i>A pyramid is a geometric figure with a closed base and triangular faces that converge at a single point at the top, known as the apex.</i>\"</li></ul></p>",
               "source": null,
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "html",
               "PostMention": ""
            },
            {
               "text": "Despite this definition, people's flexible understanding often leads to pyramids being considered even more diverse.\n\nThere are structures that resemble pyramids and are frequently classified as such. An example of this are the sacred mountains of Mesoamerica, known by the Maya as *Witz* (<htcite0>), but which are currently known by many as pyramids.",
               "source": [
                  {
                     "type": 1,
                     "uuid": "960e3a8e-3a60-4ee4-9df4-e2187489e3b9",
                     "text": "García Capistrán, H.",
                     "page": "pp. 144",
                     "date_time": {
                        "type": "gregory",
                        "year": "2018",
                        "month": "",
                        "day": ""
                     }
                  }
               ],
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "markdown",
               "PostMention": ""
            },
            {
               "text": "<p class=\"desc\"><img id=\"img4\" onclick=\"htImageZoom('img4', '0%')\" src=\"images/Xunantunich/WitzXunantunich.jpg\" class=\"imgcenter\"/><b>Figure 3</b>: Sacred mountain at Xunantunich, Belize. Photograph taken on <htdate0>, during a visit to the site.</p>",
               "source": null,
               "date_time": [
                  {
                     "type": "gregory",
                     "year": "2016",
                     "month": "7",
                     "day": "22"
                  }
               ],
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "html",
               "PostMention": ""
            },
            {
               "text": "Understanding how to count and compare created new needs for humanity, such as adding equal quantities.",
               "source": null,
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "markdown",
               "PostMention": ""
            }
         ]
      }
